   <abstract>This thesis explores the ways in which white, Christian children were centered in several religious, political, and economic movements in 1970s and 80s America. The rise of the Religious Right and the emergence of the Satanic panic caused religious reformers to believe their children were especially susceptible to manipulative cultural, corporate, and religious forces that threatened the nuclear family. This is especially salient when analyzing the ways in which the toy and television industries advertised products to children through licensed characters in the 1980s, which led several conservative Christians to detect a creeping Satanism in children's playthings. As a ubiquitous and commercialized object, Ouija boards embodied this social anxiety as games that came to be perceived as gateways to children's spiritual and physical endangerment. Although children were central to the rhetoric of politicians, parents, and religious leaders in the 1970s and 80s, the actual agency and experiences of kids disappeared in the chaos. Tracing these events and ideologies demonstrates how the concept of childhood underwent rapid change, commercialization, and politicization in mid to late twentieth-century America. In doing so, I offer several contributions to the field of religious studies, including analysis of understudied Satanic panic primary sources and innovative research on Ouija boards.</abstract>
